        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "X happened, then Y happened; therefore X caused Y.",
        "spans": []
      }
    ],
    "description": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "The Post Hoc fallacy is committed whenever one reasons to a causal conclusion based solely on the supposed cause preceding its \"effect\". Of course, it is a necessary condition of causation that the cause precede the effect, but it is not a sufficient condition. Thus, post hoc evidence may suggest the hypothesis of a causal relationship, which then requires further testing, but it is never sufficient evidence on its own.",
        "spans": [
